06792nam a22008535i 9783110419306DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104193067 a10.1515/97831104193062doi  a(DE-B1597)450710  a(OCoLC)1024042694  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0042002bisacsh00aPetrarch and Boccaccio :bThe Unity of Knowledge in the Pre-modern World /ced. by Igor Candido. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (380 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMimesis : Romanische Literaturen der Welt ,x0178-7489 ;v6100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Formation of Knowledge and Petrarch's Books -- tSacra solitudo. Petrarch's authorship and the locus sacer -- tPetrarch, Creator of the Christian Humanist -- tPetrarch and the History of Philosophy -- tThe Secret Life of Classical and Arabic Medical Texts in Petrarch's Canzoniere -- tFrom Paradox to Exclusivity: Dante and Petrarch's Lyrical Eschatologies -- tDante, Petrarch, and Boccaccio on Religious Conversion -- tThe Incipit of the Decameron: Textual Margins as an Index of Epochal Change -- tThe Proemio of the Decameron. Boccaccio's Hidden Dialogue with Scholasticism -- tBoccaccio's Novel Hecuba: Beritola between Ovid and Dante -- tBoccaccio, the Classics and the Latin Middle Ages -- tThe Inventors of Things in Boccaccio's De genealogia deorum gentilium -- tBoccaccio's Critique of Petrarch -- tThe Perfect Woman in Boccaccio and Petrarch -- tPetrarch, Boccaccio, and the Space of Vernacular Literature -- tBetween Petrarch and Boccaccio: Strategies of the End -- tContributors -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tIndex Nominum0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe early modern and modern cultural world in the West would be unthinkable without Petrarch and Boccaccio. Despite this fact, there is still no scholarly contribution entirely devoted to analysing their intellectual revolution. Internationally renowned scholars are invited to discuss and rethink the historical, intellectual, and literary roles of Petrarch and Boccaccio between the great model of Dante's encyclopedia and the ideas of a double or multifaceted culture in the era of Italian Renaissance Humanism. In his lyrical poems and Latin treatises, Petrarch created a cultural pattern that was both Christian and Classical, exercising immense influence on the Western World in the centuries to come. Boccaccio translated this pattern into his own vernacular narratives and erudite works, ultimately claiming as his own achievement the reconstructed unity of the Ancient Greek and Latin world in his contemporary age. The volume reconsiders Petrarch's and Boccaccio's heritages from different perspectives (philosophy, theology, history, philology, paleography, literature, theory), and investigates how these heritages shaped the cultural transition between the end of the Middle Ages and the early modern era, as well as European identity.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aBoccaccio, Giovanni. 4aKulturgeschichte/Mittelalter. 4aKulturgeschichte/Renaissance. 4aPetrarca, Francesco. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aCultural History (Middle Ages).  aCultural History (Renaissance).  aFrancesco Petrarch.  aGiovanni Boccaccio.1 aBragantini, Renzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandido, Igor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCan